  "chunk_index": 41,
  "summary": "Following a conversation with Colonel Baker, in which Baker expresses concern over Colin Lamb's low spirits and warns him against becoming defeated by the chaos of the world, Colin reads a newspaper report. The report states that Madame Melina Rival collapsed at Victoria Station due to exhaustion and died in the hospital after being discovered to have been stabbed.\n\nColin calls Hakastad, who reveals that he had previously visited Madame Rival. Hakastad explains his theory that Madame Rival had been paid to falsely identify a corpse as her long-abandoned husband, Harry Castleton, to protect certain business interests. Hakastad notes that after Colin's visit, Madame Rival made a phone call and subsequently traveled to Crofton during rush hour, where she was likely stabbed by a killer hiding in the crowd. Colin informs Hakastad of a witness report regarding a large laundry basket delivered to 19 Wilbraham Crescent by a man in a car from Snowflake Laundry on September 9th, before hanging up to handle his own affairs.\n\nFive days later, Colin arrives in Crofton and stays at the Clarendon Hotel. Upon waking, he receives a thick, expensive envelope containing a note that reads: \"Curlew Hotel, 11:30, Room 413 (Knock three times!)\" Noticing the room number matches the time, Colin proceeds to the Mallard Inn. He goes to Room 413 and knocks three times as instructed. Upon entering the unlocked room, he finds Hercule Poirot, who surprises him by revealing he arrived in a luxury Mercedes-Benz.",
